{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016bqD752mkaTKRSPnrY6wgY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see two issues:\n1. Elasticsearch is receiving \"plaintext http traffic on an https channel\" — the old auth-checker pod (7694fd4bc9-hsjtm) is using HTTP, and the new pod (67d57bf965-fj6pq) is also using HTTP from the probe.\n2. Authentication is failing — the logs show old password attempts failing, meaning the old auth-checker pod is still running with the old password.\n\nThe real problem is:\n- The Elasticsearch readiness probe on the es-0, es-1, es-2 pods is also using HTTP probably\n- The old auth-checker pod is still running with the outdated password from the previous secret version, while the new pod has the updated credentials but both are hitting the HTTPS endpoint with HTTP requests.\n- I'm realizing that when secrets are mounted as environment variables, they don't automatically refresh—the pod needs to be recreated, which should have happened during the deployment restart, but something's off with the probe configuration.\n- The ES pods themselves were initially running fine, but now they're all showing as not ready, which suggests their readiness probes (likely using the built-in security health check) are also failing due to the password rotation.\n- I need to check what the ES pod readiness probes actually look like to understand why they dropped from ready to not ready.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":7460,"cache_read_input_tokens":38542,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":7460},"output_tokens":21,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8da424f0-ca03-4ad2-895a-31829e591d2d","uuid":"ebb24ff0-9324-4f47-afbe-87ea2d6d107b","request_id":"r